ðŸ§  JOIN TYPES WITH EXAMPLES

1. ðŸ”— INNER JOIN

Returns records that have matching values in both tables.

SELECT e.name, d.department_name
FROM employees e
INNER JOIN departments d
  ON e.department_id = d.department_id;

ðŸ“Œ Matches employees with their departments.

2. â¬…ï¸ LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN)

Returns all records from the left table, and matched records from the right table.

SELECT e.name, d.department_name
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN departments d
  ON e.department_id = d.department_id;

ðŸ“Œ Includes employees even if no department is assigned (e.g., interns or new hires).

3. âž¡ï¸ RIGHT JOIN (RIGHT OUTER JOIN)

Returns all records from the right table, and matched records from the left.

SELECT e.name, d.department_name
FROM employees e
RIGHT JOIN departments d
  ON e.department_id = d.department_id;

ðŸ“Œ Includes departments even if no employee is assigned.

4. ðŸ”„ FULL OUTER JOIN

Returns all records when there is a match in either table.

SELECT e.name, d.department_name
FROM employees e
FULL OUTER JOIN departments d
  ON e.department_id = d.department_id;

ðŸ“Œ Combines results of LEFT and RIGHT JOIN.

5. ðŸ”ƒ CROSS JOIN

Returns a Cartesian product â€” all combinations of rows between tables.

SELECT e.name, d.department_name
FROM employees e
CROSS JOIN departments d;

ðŸ“Œ For 5 employees and 4 departments, this gives 5 Ã— 4 = 20 rows.

6. ðŸ” SELF JOIN

A table joined to itself â€” useful for organizational hierarchy.

SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m
  ON e.manager_id = m.emp_id;

ðŸ“Œ Lists each employee with their managerâ€™s name.

7. ðŸ§® NON-EQUI JOIN (Range-based Join)

A join based on inequality condition (>, <, BETWEEN, etc.), not =.

Use Case: Match employeesâ€™ salaries to bonus slabs in sales_targets.

SELECT e.name, e.salary, s.bonus_percent
FROM employees e
JOIN sales_targets s
  ON e.salary BETWEEN s.min_sales AND s.max_sales;

ðŸ“Œ Assigns bonus percentage based on salary range â€” common in incentive systems.


ðŸ§¾ Summary of JOIN Types

JOIN Type	Use Case
INNER JOIN	Matching rows in both tables
LEFT JOIN	All from left + matched from right
RIGHT JOIN	All from right + matched from left
FULL OUTER JOIN	All from both, matched and unmatched
CROSS JOIN	All combinations of rows
SELF JOIN	Compare rows within same table (e.g., manager)
NON-EQUI JOIN	Use inequality conditions (e.g., ranges)
